#CSD #CSDVirtual #CenterWeGotThis

Our Center Athletics 58 Ist Varsity Football home game is Today, Sept 4 @ 7:00 vs. Marshall. Please remember the new COVID-19 Athletics and Activities guidelines will be implemented, including capacity limitations of 100 spectators for outdoor events as directed by Jackson County.

For Center, the football team has been allotted 50 spectator game tickets. The visiting team will also be allowed 50 spectators. Only individuals with a ticket or staff essential to working the game will be allowed to enter the stadium.

The Spectator guidelines are posted on the athletic website: https://chsathletics.sportngin.com
Thank you! #CSD #GoYellowjackets

post_text: Starting next week, we will begin to welcome back small groups of our diverse learners for face-to-face instruction as written in the CENTERed on Learning Re-Entry Plan. Parents and Guardians of the small group of learners who will visit our buildings have already been notified and agreed to engage in the program. With small groups of students in our buildings, we want to take the opportunity to remind all members of our Center School District community the importance of our CSD COVID-19 expectations with a focus on the CSD 5 Fundamentals. post_text:
Good News Center School District Families,

The YMCA has recently received a grant and can now reduce costs for Center School District children to attend this program. You will receive all-day childcare and virtual learning assistance for $8.75 per day, totaling $43. 75 weekly. First preference for enrollment will be given to parents who enroll their child before Thursday, September 3rd.

To enroll, go to http://www.kansascityymca.org and click on the ‚ÄúBefore and After School Y Club‚Äù option under Programs on the main page. From there you can access the Learning Academy page. Simply choose the Center Red Bridge tab and enroll. If you need assistance or have questions, call us at (816) 360-3390 or email yclubsupport@kansascityymca.org and we will help with your specific situation.

Thank you,
Center School District Leadership

post_text:
One of our former Center School District students, Avrion Jackson, will be featured in a Black Lives Matter Mural Art project happening across the city.

On Sept. 5, six streets will be closed so artists can participate and create.

It is called KC Art on The Block: A Black Lives Matter Project, and it will paint the message that's being shared all over the world.

Jackson's mural will be at 10th and Baltimore streets.

Mural locations:
10th and Baltimore
18th and Vine
31st and Troost
63rd and Troost
63rd and Brookside Boulevard
NW Briarcliff Parkway and N. Mulberry

KMBC 9 interviewed her and shared her story. It is great to see our former students making such an impact on our community. #CSDProud #CenterSD

Online Residency (OLR) is open for PreK-12 Center School District students. Complete the entire OLR process by August 18 to guarantee your child can start on the currently scheduled 1st day of school, August 24. Applications may take up to 48 hours. Visit: https://www.center.k12.mo.us/registration for more info.

We understand, there are still many questions that remain uncertain regarding the 2020-2021 school year. At this time, we are monitoring numbers, working with public health officials and government agencies to determine the best course of action. As we explore, we are looking at options that may include starting after the currently slated first day of school August 24, 2020 and potentially looking at more virtual options for students. However, we still need students enrolled in our system. Thank you for your partnership to help us complete the Online Residency Process. We will continue to navigate the fluid situation and share more information as it becomes available. #CSD #CenterSchools

post_text:
We are excited to celebrate our Class of 2020 graduates on Tuesday, July 28, 2020 under the stars. Please visit https://www.center.k12.mo.us/covid-19 and click on the tab under graduation to help answer questions about when to arrive, where to park what will be expected.

Starlight Theatre is requiring all participants and attendees wear masks and undergo a temperature check before entry. We have purchased masks for all graduates and staff members. Starlight Theater has also created a process to social distance and you will be asked to sit in assigned seats.

The Ticket Pick Up Process: Students must pick up tickets at Center High School between Tuesday, July 21 through Friday, July 24 from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m. daily. Each student will receive 4 tickets. Tickets will have seat numbers and families or friends must sit together in blocks of 4. All guests must sit in their assigned seats to allow for proper social distancing guidelines.

#CSD #CenterSchools #2020Grad

shared_text:
Mark Potter is with Kamisha Stanton and 10 others.
June 12 at 4:19 AM ¬∑

What does racial healing look like for me? In part, it looks like this amazing team of diverse friends who are fighting to break the cycle of poverty for homeless families in the Center School District.

I am humbled to share that today Impact Center Schools / Serve the World Charities was officially approved for a $103,384 grant by the KCMO City Council. Thank you, God!

Martin Luther King Jr. said, ‚ÄúI believe we ought to do all we can to lift ourselves by our own bootstraps, but it‚Äôs a cruel jest to say to a bootless man that he ought to lift himself by his own bootstraps.‚Äù

This money will help provide boots to those who were once bootless. It will also give us the ability to pay for upfront housing costs required for stable, dignified housing. Finally, it will afford us the privilege of continuing to walk with our families until their youngest child graduates from high school.

Because no child should have to worry about where they are going to sleep tonight.

*** Openings still available.*******
During the 2020-2021 academic school year, Center School District will offer 36 prekindergarten openings for children whose families do not meet Head Start or Early Childhood Special Education requirements. These openings will only be available to children who are four and in their final year before kindergarten. Early childhood programming will be offered Monday - Thursdays from 8:00 - 3:00 and Fridays from 8:00 - 11:30. Of the 36 openings, 18 slots will be reserved for families who qualify for the free and reduced lunch program and will not be asked to pay a fee. The other 18 slots will be reserved for parents who will pay $50.00 a week. Program placement will be made based on full application completion and students will be chosen based on a lottery system. #CenterSD #CenterProud

post_text: The new turf field is underway at Center High School, while buildings are closed for health precautions. Thanks to the the NFL Foundation, this project is just one more example of how our community, in partnership with the NFL Foundation and the KcChiefs are working hard to provide first class opportunities for kids. We are excited to begin work on this project and hope community members will join us to see the great things that we are accomplishing together and will celebrate when it is safe again to gather. #ThankYou #CenterWeGotThis #CSD

‚Ä¢ Each student may pick up four meals (two breakfasts/two lunches) on Monday/Wednesday and two meals (one breakfast/one lunch) on Friday.
‚Ä¢ Students no longer need to be present to receive a meal; parents/guardians may pick up meals for their child(ren).

We are ordering all Missouri public and charter schools to remain closed through the remainder of the academic year with the exceptions of nutrition services and child care that are outlined in our recent health order.

shared_text:
City of Kansas City, Mo. Government is with Mike Severo.
March 30 at 3:42 PM ¬∑ Kansas City, MO ¬∑

Did you know that April 1, 2020 is #Census Day? A fair and accurate census count is essential to numerous aspects of civic life, from allocation of billions of dollars in federal funds in Kansas City, MO alone, to political representation at all levels of government.

There are only seven questions to complete, and the Census should take about 10 minutes to complete. Let's make sure #KCMO stands up and gets counted.

For more information, please visit http://kcmo.gov/census.
#CountMeInKC #Census2020 #KansasCity #Missouri

We are pleased to announce a partnership with Sodexo USA and Student Transportation of America to deliver free meals to Center School District students.

‚Ä¢ Starting Monday, March 23 sack meals (breakfast and lunch) will be delivered to various stops throughout the District and will also be available for pick-up in the parking lots of each elementary school.
‚Ä¢ These deliveries will happen Monday through Friday through April 3.

‚Ä¢ We ask that families walk to stops and do not drive to ensure safety.
‚Ä¢ We also ask that you follow all health recommendations and practice social distancing.
‚Ä¢ Students will need to be present to receive the meals.
‚Ä¢ Attached is more time and location information.
‚Ä¢ Lead To Read has also donated free books for students (elementary level). Those will be available at stops and the elementary parking lots on Monday.
‚Ä¢ If you have questions, you may call 816.349.3300 M-F 8:00 ‚Äì 4:00.

post_text:
We are excited to welcome Dr. Yolanda Cargile, incoming Center School District Superintendent, to meet Center Staff.

Dr. Cargile is a Missouri native graduating from Ruskin High School. Over her tenure as an educator, Dr. Cargile has served as a social worker, tutor, mentor, middle school teacher, building principal, district level administrator and adjunct instructor. She currently serves as the Superintendent of the Hickman Mills School District.

Community members are invited to meet Dr. Cargile on Monday March 23, 2020 at 5:00 at Boone Elementary.

post_text: CHS Scholar Bowl team competed at MCC-Maple Woods Scholar Bowl on March 3. Out of 20 teams your Jackets team left the Preliminary round in first place but only by 1 point. In fact the top four teams were separated by 2 points after 120 questions. In the final round, the top four teams competed and after 90 more questions, your Jackets found themselves in fourth place only five points behind the first place team. It was a very competitive day and the Yellowjacket Scholar Bowl team performed extremely well. Congrats to Joseph Ezuego, Reina Gray, Ashly Mota-Perez, Bronwynne Miller, and Benjamin Lahann! #CenterSD #CenterProud

We are looking forward to building a bright future at Center School District and want to invite YOU to attend the formal kickoff to celebrate with our community! The official groundbreaking ceremony will be held Thursday, March 5th at 10:00am.

Eighty-Two percent of Center School District voters approved the 48 million dollar no-tax-increase bond in April, 2019. We promised voters we would enhance safety and security efforts, upgrade infrastructure and maintenance projects, provide early childhood and elementary building updates as well as build a new Indian Creek Elementary.

We will have a short program recognizing students, alumni and those who have worked to educate the community to make this happen for students and teachers.

Newkirk Novak Construction Partners Hollis + Miller Architects
Indian Creek Elementary Alumni

We are so proud of all of our students- they have such bright futures and today we are spotlighting Reina Gray, a senior at Center High School! Reina will attend NYU‚Äôs Tisch School of the Arts this fall to pursue a BFA in dance. #CenterSD #CenterProud

https://www.facebook.com/cityinmotiondancetheater/photos/a.483278817748/10157058808822749/?type=3
shared_text:
City in Motion Dance Theater, Inc.
January 24 at 12:35 AM ¬∑

Introducing Modern Night at the Folly choreographer Reina Gray, a senior at Center High School! Reina will attend NYU‚Äôs Tisch School of the Arts this fall to pursue a BFA in dance. She has been training at The Pulse ‚Ä™Performing Arts Center‚Ä¨ in south Kansas City since 2008. Reina has spent summers training at ‚Ä™Kansas City Ballet‚Ä¨, Alonzo King Lines Ballet, NYU Tisch, Hubbard Street Dance and Paul Taylor American Modern Dance. A proud alumna of Defy Dance Project, Reina has been privileged to again work with Haley Kostas in the collaborative RubiX Project. First Impact is a traffic safety program that educates parents about Missouri‚Äôs Graduated Driver License (GDL) law.

January 10 at 3:41 PM ¬∑ Kansas City, MO ¬∑

The Kansas City Symphony hosted a special community concert with 100 % of the proceeds benefiting the fine art programs. The world class musicians spent the day rehearsing and speaking to students and performed for a full house on Wednesday night. This concert was part of The Bill and Peggy Lyons Support School Music program, that was established in 2003 in order to provide area school districts the opportunity to host the Kansas City Symphony and raise funding in support of fine arts programs. Since its inception, local school music programs have raised more than $170,000 in revenue as a direct result of Support School Music.

post_text:
We are thrilled to recognize cross-country participants Brandon Chandler and Ben Lahann along with their coach, Christian Nord.

Coach Nord commented that Brandon Chandler was his most improved runner. He said ‚ÄúBrandon consistently showed improvement throughout the season. He got faster and faster as the season progressed, cutting time at 7 different meets. He ended up running a 5K 3 minutes faster than he did last season.‚Äù Great job Brandon!

Coach Nord shared Ben Lahann earned a medal at 10 out of his 11 meets. He took home 1st place at two separate meets with 5 top 5 finishes. He was able to get under the elusive 18-minute mark, running at 17:52. Ben became the first Center male since 2008 to qualify for the Missouri State Cross Country Championships. Congratulations Ben and great job to you both! #CenterSD #CenterProud

shared_text:
Center Middle School- Kansas City
November 16, 2019 at 5:12 PM ¬∑

One of our 6th grade students, Niveah Bell, started her own charitable organization when she was 8 years old. Niveah wanted to make the world a little better by donating items to the homeless around the holidays. This year marks the 5th year she will be collecting and delivering items to individuals in need. Niveah has a goal of collecting enough for 150 care packages to be delivered. The Student Leaders of CMS heard about Niveah's mission and wanted to help her reach her goal. Therefore, we will be having a penny war next week (November 18-22) to support this cause!

Link below is a news story about Nivea and Heart to Heart when she was just 8 years old.

https://www.ketv.com/article/kc-girl-helps-the-homeless-in-omaha/8537566

post_text: So proud!
shared_text:
Jennifer White Willard‚ÄéCenter Middle School PTO
November 17, 2019 at 4:48 PM ¬∑

What a weekend!! Yesterday was the Regional Robotics Tournament. This was by far the biggest undertaking our PTO has ever done. Countless hours of planning, discussing, preparing, and crunching numbers. I honestly had a dream team and I can't say thank you enough to the handful of ladies who who went all in with me these past 6 weeks!! We had amazing PTO members who worked tirelessly yesterday selling dipping dots, cotton candy, filling orders, and so much more!! Thank you to each of you! It was a huge success!!!
(Only picture I took was during one of our quiet periods in the afternoon)

post_text:
This Saturday Center School District will be hosting two FIRST Robotic competitive events. Center High School has the privilege of welcoming 26 teams (over 235 students) along with coaches, mentors and parents to the Center High School FIRST Tech challenge meets.

Center Middle School will welcome 28 teams from across the Kansas City region to the FIRST Lego Robotics regional Qualifier.

The Center Alternative Robotics team will also compete in the afternoon meet at Center High School. The Center High School Robotics teams and Center Middle School FIRST Tech Challenge team will actually help run the meets and serve as queuers, referees and score keepers.

A big thank you to Derrick Prewitt who will serve as Tournament Director for the FIRST Lego Robotics event at Center Middle School. He has put a lot of hard work into recruiting volunteers, planning and coordinating this event for the over 250 students across the Kansas City Area.

As always thank you for your support of our students and our robotics programs. #CSD #CenterSD

Our Center Education Foundation Board of Directors, mostly Center alumni, have committed to help end homelessness for Center students by supporting a community based program called Impact Center. This program works individually with our families who don't have stable housing to help them overcome barriers to successfully finding and staying in permanent housing to end their merry-go-round of instability.
Thank you Councilwoman Andrea Bough and @SlyJames with Wickham James Strategies and Solutions for coming out to support the efforts! #CenterSD #CenterImpact #CenterProud

text:
Our Center Education Foundation Board of Directors, mostly Center alumni, have committed to help end homelessness for Center students by supporting a community based program called Impact Center. This program works individually with our families who don't have stable housing to help them overcome barriers to successfully finding and staying in permanent housing to end their merry-go-round of instability.
Thank you Councilwoman Andrea Bough and @SlyJames with Wickham James Strategies and Solutions for coming out to support the efforts! #CenterSD #CenterImpact #CenterProud

We are excited that next Tuesday our Elementary 3-5th students will have the chance to meet author Derrick Barnes. Barnes is from Kansas City, MO. He is a graduate of Jackson State University with a BA degree in Marketing. He is the author of the critically acclaimed picture book CROWN: An Ode To The Fresh Cut (Denene Millner Books/Agate Bolden) which won a multitude of literay awards, making it one of the most decorated picture books in the history of children‚Äôs literature.

This is a student centered event, however Mid-Continent Public Library- Red Bridge Branch will also host Mr. Barnes. Families may register by going to mymcpl.org. #CSD #CenterSD

Another fantastic day of collaboration at Herndon, this time amongst educators. Started the day collaborating about career education and workforce development with secondary counselors from Raytown, Hickman Mills, Center, Grandview, Independence, and Lee's Summit. Ended the evening with a SkillsUSA All-Advisor dinner with instructors and administrators from Cass Career Center, Manual Career and Technical Center, Lex La-Ray Technical Ctr., Warrensburg Area Career Center, The Career & Technology Center at Fort Osage, Summit Technology Academy, and Clinton Technical School getting together to begin planning leadership and skill contests for students.

Sports Medicine Center at Children's Mercy
September 17, 2019 at 5:52 PM ¬∑

Here are this week's winners for the Performance of the Week - Olathe Public Schools (Northwest) Brooke Illum and Center School District Cris Ferrer. Congratulations!

Illum, a senior gymnast, posted the best individual performance at the 12-team Firebird Invitational. She was 1st in All Around, floor and vault, and 2nd on the beam and bars.

Ferrer, a senior running back, rushed for three TDs in Center's 41-10 win Friday night. He finished with 187 total yards, including 115 on the ground, 49 yards receiving and a 25-yard kickoff return.

To nominate a student-athlete for next week, submit here: https://www.childrensmercy.org/performanceoftheweek/

post_text:
The Kansas City Chiefs have announced their first Coach of the Week honors for the 2019 season. The awards go to Center High School coach Bryan DeLong and Blue Valley West coach Josh Koerkenmeier.

As a result of this honor, both schools will receive a $500 player health and safety grant from the Hunt Family Foundation. Each school will also receive a Gatorade Sideline Kit, including coolers, bottles and Gatorade products. Additionally, both coaches will be presented congratulatory footballs autographed by Chiefs Head Coach Andy Reid and a certificate recognizing their selection.

Center beat St. Joseph Lafayette 35-21 to move to 2-0 on the season.

‚ÄúWe are extremely honored to be recognized by such a class organization as the Kansas City Chiefs,‚Äù DeLong said. ‚ÄúThey have set the bar when it comes to class and winning. A truly humbling experience for the Yellowjackets.‚Äù Thank You @GarySpani for supporting our students and teams.
